Model Inferences

Kristian Brock

17 September, 2019

Modelling of the event rates in the observed series is presented in DLTSeriesPresentation and ObjRespSeriesPresentation. Inferences beyond those series-specific insights are explored here.

DLT Model

Fitted series

dlt %>% 
  left_join(studies, by = 'Study') %>% 
  left_join(manuscripts, by = 'Manuscript') %>% 
  filter(DoseVaryingTreatmentType %in% c('Chemotherapy', 
                                         'Radiotherapy', 
                                         'Monoclonal Antibody', 
                                         'Inhibitor')) %>% 
  add_fitted_draws(dlt_mod) %>%
  mutate(EstProbEvent = .value / n) %>% 
  summarise(EstProbEvent = mean(EstProbEvent)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = DoseLevel, y = EstProbEvent, group = AnalysisSeriesId,

  xlim(-5, 5) +
  labs(title = 'Fitted dose-DLT curves', col = 'Drug type', y = 'Prob(DLT)') + 
  theme(legend.position = 'none')

Adjustments to baseline DLT rate for dose-varying-treatment type

dlt_mod %>% 
    spread_draws(r_DoseVaryingTreatmentType[TmtType,term]) %>%
    filter(TmtType %in% c('Radiotherapy', 'Monoclonal.Antibody', 
                          'Chemotherapy', 'Inhibitor')) %>% 
    filter(term == 'Intercept') %>% 
    rename(ParamValue = r_DoseVaryingTreatmentType) %>% 
  mutate(TmtTypeO = factor(TmtType, levels = c('Monoclonal.Antibody',
                                                   'Radiotherapy',
                                                   'Inhibitor',
                                                   'Chemotherapy'), 
                               ordered = TRUE)) %>%
  filter(term == 'Intercept') %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y = TmtTypeO, group = TmtTypeO, fill = TmtTypeO, 
             x = ParamValue)) + 
  geom_density_ridges() + 
  labs(x = 'Adjustment to log(odds) of DLT compared to entire dataset', 
       y = 'Treatment type',
       title = 'Distributions of baseline rates of DLT') +
  theme(legend.position = 'none') + 
  xlim(-1.75, 2.5)

After adjusting for the heterogeneity seen in the individual series, it appears that chemo is probably the therapy type with the greatest average risk of DLT. However, with inhibitors and radiotherapy, the risk of DLT is almost the same. The similarity in baseline rates may suggest that DLT is chosen mindful of therapy to be something that is likely to occur in a set proportion of patients. However, this would require admirable forecasting skills from trialists. Notably, incidence of DLT is less common in monoclonal antibodies.

dlt_mod %>%

  filter(TmtType %in% c('Radiotherapy', 'Monoclonal.Antibody', 'Chemotherapy', 
                        'Inhibitor')) %>% 
  mutate(TmtTypeO = factor(TmtType, levels = c('Monoclonal.Antibody',
                                               'Radiotherapy',
                                               'Inhibitor',
                                               'Chemotherapy'), 
                           ordered = TRUE)) %>%
  filter(term == 'DoseLevel') %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y = TmtTypeO, group = TmtTypeO, fill = TmtTypeO, 
             x = r_DoseVaryingTreatmentType)) + 
  geom_density_ridges() + 
  labs(x = 'Adjustment to gradient with respect to dose', 
       y = 'Treatment type',
       title = 'Distribution of sensitivity of DLT to dose increases') +
  theme(legend.position = 'none') + 
  xlim(-1, 1)

TODO - these need DoseLevel effect adding in now. With chemotherapies, inhibitors, and radiotherapy, the relationship of DLT risk with dose is concincingly positive. That is, greater doses of these treatments are associated with greater risk of DLT. The message is rather more opaque with antibodies. The aggregate evidence supports a positive relationship, but the strenght of the relationship is rather weaker than the other drug classes and could plausbily be very small.

Objective Response Model

Fitted series

obj_resp %>% 
  filter(n > 0) %>% 
  left_join(studies, by = 'Study') %>% 
  left_join(manuscripts, by = 'Manuscript') %>% 
  filter(DoseVaryingTreatmentType %in% c('Chemotherapy', 
                                         'Radiotherapy', 
                                         'Monoclonal Antibody', 
                                         'Inhibitor')) %>% 
  add_fitted_draws(obj_resp_mod) %>%
  mutate(EstProbEvent = .value / n) %>% 
  summarise(EstProbEvent = mean(EstProbEvent)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = DoseLevel, y = EstProbEvent, group = AnalysisSeriesId, 
             col = DoseVaryingTreatmentType)) + 
  geom_line(size = 1) + 
  facet_wrap(~ DoseVaryingTreatmentType, ncol = 2) + 
  xlim(-5, 5) +
  labs(title = 'Fitted dose-response curves', col = 'Drug type', 
       y = 'Prob(ObjectiveResponse)') + 
  theme(legend.position = 'none')

Some series have seen no response at all. These could be medically inert molecules. Label the series:

obj_resp %>% count(AnalysisSeriesId) %>% nrow  # 93 series
[1] 93
# Tox in efficacious vs non-efficacious series
obj_resp %>% 
  group_by(AnalysisSeriesId) %>% 
  filter(n > 0) %>% 
  summarise(TotalResp = sum(Events), TotalN = sum(n)) %>% 
  mutate(RespRate = TotalResp / TotalN) %>% 
  filter(TotalResp > 0) %>% 
  mutate(Class = 'Responses seen') -> efficacious_series
efficacious_series %>% nrow  # 61 series
[1] 61
obj_resp %>% 
  group_by(AnalysisSeriesId) %>% 
  filter(n > 0) %>% 
  summarise(TotalResp = sum(Events), TotalN = sum(n)) %>% 
  mutate(RespRate = TotalResp / TotalN) %>% 
  filter(TotalResp == 0) %>% 
  mutate(Class = 'No responses seen') -> non_efficacious_series
non_efficacious_series %>% nrow  # 32 series
[1] 32
obj_resp %>% 
  filter(n > 0) %>% 
  left_join(studies, by = 'Study') %>% 
  left_join(manuscripts, by = 'Manuscript') %>% 
  left_join(bind_rows(efficacious_series, non_efficacious_series), 
            by = 'AnalysisSeriesId') %>% 
  filter(DoseVaryingTreatmentType %in% c('Chemotherapy', 
                                         'Radiotherapy', 
                                         'Monoclonal Antibody', 
                                         'Inhibitor')) %>% 
  filter(Class == 'Responses seen') %>% 
  add_fitted_draws(obj_resp_mod) %>%
  mutate(EstProbEvent = .value / n) %>% 
  summarise(EstProbEvent = mean(EstProbEvent)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = DoseLevel, y = EstProbEvent, group = AnalysisSeriesId, 
             col = DoseVaryingTreatmentType)) + 
  geom_line(size = 1) + 
  facet_wrap(~ DoseVaryingTreatmentType, ncol = 2) + 
  xlim(-5, 5) +
  labs(title = 'Fitted dose-response curves', col = 'Drug type', 
       y = 'Prob(ObjectiveResponse)') + 
  theme(legend.position = 'none')
